This is a page-by-page text document, output of a standalone scanning-OCR process [OmniPage, Abby], encapsulated in a pdf container - regretably so. It couldn't be determined whether the file was thus released by its creator, or was subsequently modified by a different party: this is the only version in existence. As a consequence of this state of affairs, there was necessary a lenghty processing in order to free the text. The best, but not perfect, output was obtained as Word document (doc) with Nitro PDF. The text was then parsed 6 times in order to capture and correct (most) rendering errors. The headings (outline levels) and the table of contents had to be created anew.   The only significant modification from the original was the supression of page breaks in order to obtain a neat text reflow. Original page numbers were preserved and integrated into the flowing text discretely, but visibly [red font on grey background]. As a nod to the physical book which was typeset in New Baskerville, the font has been changed accordingly.  The html is Word 'filtered html' output: this cleans the code from most Microsoft specific styles, while preserving enough information for the recreation of the original Word doc file. This is why the html was not run though Tidy. In order to create a continuous html file, 'merge' the epub sections in Sigil. The resulting html, opened in Word, will recreate the doc. However, the table of contents will have to be recreated (not the headings, just some of the links/anchors).  Thanks to the original scanner & proofreader for making available the P2P edition. I hope that in the future painstakingly created text scans will no longer be pointlessly imprisoned in pdf containers. [UL] P2P ePub v 1.0
